<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,672,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
Myco-heterotrophic, monoecious 
<emphasis box="[553,618,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">herbs</emphasis>
, up to 
<quantity box="[703,762,672,698]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="cm" value="9.0">9 cm</quantity>
tall, hyaline, glabrous; stem unbranched. 
<emphasis box="[1261,1328,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Roots</emphasis>
filiform. 
<emphasis box="[151,233,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Leaves</emphasis>
absent. 
<emphasis box="[332,490,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Inflorescence</emphasis>
racemose, terminal, bracteate, up to six flowered, or solitary flower; bracteoles 1.0–1.5 × 0.5–1.0 mm, ensiform to triangular, apex acute; flowers 2–3 × 
<quantity box="[1026,1128,749,775]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
, actinomorphic, bisexual; pedicel 
<quantity box="[248,348,788,814]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3 mm</quantity>
long, tepals 4–6, persistent, 1–2 × 0.5–1.0 mm, isomorphic, deltoid, with a central vein prominent, caudate, 
<quantity box="[389,529,826,852]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.5 mm</quantity>
long; ovary&gt; 35, papillose, apocarpic, surrounding the androecium, style up to 
<quantity box="[184,254,865,891]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
long., lateral; stamens 3–4, persistent, inserted at the edge of receptacle, anthers 
<quantity box="[1281,1433,865,891]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="0.35" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.5 mm</quantity>
, globoid. 
<emphasis box="[255,326,904,929]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Fruits</emphasis>
achenes, up to 
<quantity box="[508,568,904,930]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="1.0">1mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,672,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,268,942,968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Notes</emphasis>
:—Previous to this study, 
<taxonomicName box="[579,719,943,968]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[579,719,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Lacandonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered to be a monotypic genus, represented by 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.Martinez S. &amp; Ramos" authorityYear="1989" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schismatica">L. schismatica</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which is known only from the Lacandon region in 
<collectingRegion box="[914,1012,981,1007]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1025,1115,981,1007]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H." box="[1131,1431,981,1007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="128 - 135" refId="ref2203" refString="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H. (1989) Lacandoniaceae (Triuridales): Una nueva familia de Mexico. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 128 - 135." type="journal article" year="1989">Martínez &amp; Ramos 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ambrose, B. A. &amp; Espinosa-Matias, S. &amp; Vazquez-Santana, S. &amp; Vergara-Silva, F. &amp; Martinez, E. &amp; Marquez-Guzman, J. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R." box="[151,402,1020,1046]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="15 - 35" refId="ref1685" refString="Ambrose, B. A., Espinosa-Matias, S., Vazquez-Santana, S., Vergara-Silva, F., Martinez, E., Marquez-Guzman, J. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R. (2006) Comparative developmental series of the Mexican triurids support a euanthial interpretation for the unusual reproductive axes of Lacandonia schismatica (Triuridaceae). American Journal of Botany 93: 15 - 35." type="journal article" year="2006">
Ambrose 
<emphasis box="[268,329,1020,1045]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). It was previously placed in a separate family, 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1170,1020,1046]" class="Liliopsida" family="Lacandoniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lacandoniaceae</taxonomicName>
, because it is the only angiosperm in which the ovaries surround the androecium. It also has an apocarpic ovary, three to four central stamens, and bilocular, transversely dehiscent anthers (
<bibRefCitation author="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H." box="[831,1143,1097,1123]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="128 - 135" refId="ref2203" refString="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H. (1989) Lacandoniaceae (Triuridales): Una nueva familia de Mexico. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 128 - 135." type="journal article" year="1989">Martínez &amp; Ramos 1989</bibRefCitation>
). Later, the species was placed in 
<taxonomicName box="[266,413,1136,1162]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Triuridaceae</taxonomicName>
(Maas-van de Kamer &amp; Weustenfeld 1998, 
<bibRefCitation author="APG II" box="[934,1086,1136,1162]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="399 - 436" refId="ref1759" refString="APG II (2003) An update of the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group classification for the orders and families of flowering plants: APG II. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 141: 399 - 436." type="journal article" year="2003">
APG 
<date box="[1001,1086,1136,1162]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" value="2003-02">II 2003</date>
</bibRefCitation>
). The atypical position of the gynoecium and androecium is suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mabberley, D. J." box="[670,882,1174,1200]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" refId="ref2169" refString="Mabberley, D. J. (2008) Mabberley's Plant-book, a portable dictionary of plants, their classifications, and uses. Cambridge University Press, New York, 1040 p." type="book" year="2008">Mabberley (2008)</bibRefCitation>
as a possible case of homeotic mutation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,672,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
The genus was previously known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[773,863,1213,1239]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and was considered endemic to that country (
<bibRefCitation author="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H." box="[158,456,1252,1278]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="128 - 135" refId="ref2203" refString="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H. (1989) Lacandoniaceae (Triuridales): Una nueva familia de Mexico. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 128 - 135." type="journal article" year="1989">Martínez &amp; Ramos 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ambrose, B. A. &amp; Espinosa-Matias, S. &amp; Vazquez-Santana, S. &amp; Vergara-Silva, F. &amp; Martinez, E. &amp; Marquez-Guzman, J. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R." box="[469,715,1252,1278]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="15 - 35" refId="ref1685" refString="Ambrose, B. A., Espinosa-Matias, S., Vazquez-Santana, S., Vergara-Silva, F., Martinez, E., Marquez-Guzman, J. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R. (2006) Comparative developmental series of the Mexican triurids support a euanthial interpretation for the unusual reproductive axes of Lacandonia schismatica (Triuridaceae). American Journal of Botany 93: 15 - 35." type="journal article" year="2006">
Ambrose 
<emphasis box="[584,644,1252,1277]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). Our record of populations of a taxon belonging to the same genus in 
<collectingCountry box="[266,342,1290,1316]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Brazil</collectingCountry>
is therefore the first in South America. It is a remarkable case of disjunction between Mesoamerica and the Brazilian Coastal Forest. The Brazilian specimens, here described as the new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Melo &amp; M. Alves" authorityYear="2012" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">L. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, fit within the morphological characterization of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.Martinez S. &amp; Ramos" authorityYear="1989" box="[845,1013,1368,1393]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schismatica">
<emphasis box="[845,1013,1368,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">L. schismatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, albeit at the lower range of number of ovaries and plant size as cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H." box="[587,902,1406,1432]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="128 - 135" refId="ref2203" refString="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H. (1989) Lacandoniaceae (Triuridales): Una nueva familia de Mexico. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 128 - 135." type="journal article" year="1989">Martínez &amp; Ramos (1989)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Vergara-Silva, F. &amp; Espinosa-Matias, S. &amp; Ambrose, B. A. &amp; Vazquez-Santana, S. &amp; Martinez-Mena, A. &amp; Marquez-Guzman, J. &amp; Martinez, E. &amp; Meyerowitz, E. M. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R." box="[961,1282,1406,1432]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="345 - 357" refId="ref2240" refString="Vergara-Silva, F., Espinosa-Matias, S., Ambrose, B. A., Vazquez-Santana, S., Martinez-Mena, A., Marquez-Guzman, J., Martinez, E. Meyerowitz, E. M. &amp; Alvarez-Buylla, E. R. (2003) Inside-out flowers characteristic of Lacandonia schismatica evolved at least before its divergence from a closely related taxon, Triuris brevistylis. International Journal of Plant Sciences 164: 345 - 357." type="journal article" year="2003">
Vergara-Silva 
<emphasis box="[1132,1191,1407,1432]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Melo &amp; M. Alves" authorityYear="2012" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Lacandonia brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[430,589,1445,1470]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schimatica">
<emphasis box="[430,589,1445,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">L. schimatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having solitary flowers or inflorescences with up to six flowers, and more than 35 papillose ovaries. Molecular studies, comparing Mexican and Brazilian specimens could resolve the question if these geographically isolated populations should actually be treated as different species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,672,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Melo &amp; M. Alves" authorityYear="2012" box="[198,465,1561,1586]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis box="[198,465,1561,1586]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Lacandonia brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in the extreme north of the Atlantic Forest in northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1284,1359,1561,1587]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[245,336,1600,1626]" country="Brazil" name="Paraiba" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Paraíba</collectingRegion>
, about 
<quantity box="[421,495,1600,1626]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="km" value="20.0">20 km</quantity>
from the coast, a region with an average maximum annual temperature of 26ºC and rainfall of 
<quantity box="[322,442,1638,1664]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="1700.0">1,700 mm</quantity>
/year. It grows in sandy soil in semideciduous forest with a canopy around 
<quantity box="[1310,1370,1638,1664]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
high. The forest fragments in the study area are distinguished by the high diversity of trees. Neither selective wood cutting nor other kind of human disturbance was observed in the area. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Melo &amp; M. Alves" authorityYear="2012" box="[973,1240,1716,1741]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis box="[973,1240,1716,1741]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Lacandonia brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in moist, organic, and decomposing substrate and found fertile in August and September.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,672,2012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H." box="[361,675,1793,1819]" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" pagination="128 - 135" refId="ref2203" refString="Martinez, E. &amp; Ramos, C. H. (1989) Lacandoniaceae (Triuridales): Una nueva familia de Mexico. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 128 - 135." type="journal article" year="1989">Martínez &amp; Ramos (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.Martinez S. &amp; Ramos" authorityYear="1989" box="[687,857,1793,1818]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schismatica">
<emphasis box="[687,857,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">L. schismatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
blooms throughout the year in 
<collectingCountry box="[1229,1322,1793,1819]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, but most numerously so in November and December. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Melo &amp; M. Alves" authorityYear="2012" box="[684,955,1832,1857]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" genus="Lacandonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis box="[684,955,1832,1857]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Lacandonia brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
blooms in August and September. They are distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[630,780,1870,1896]" class="Liliopsida" family="Triuridaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Triuridaceae</taxonomicName>
mainly by its bisexual flowers with apocarpic ovaries surrounding the androecium, and the hyaline stem. It occurs in sympatry with other myco-heterotrophic species such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Benth.) Benth. &amp; Hook." authorityName="Benth. &amp; Hook." baseAuthorityName="Benth." box="[335,938,1948,1974]" class="Liliopsida" family="Burmanniaceae" genus="Gymnosiphon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="divaricatus">
<emphasis box="[335,637,1948,1973]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Gymnosiphon divaricatus</emphasis>
(Benth.) Benth. &amp; Hook.
</taxonomicName>
f. (
<taxonomicName box="[968,1156,1948,1974]" class="Liliopsida" family="Burmanniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Burmanniaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Aubl." authorityName="Aubl." box="[1176,1436,1948,1974]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Voyria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caerulea">
<emphasis box="[1176,1362,1948,1973]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Voyria caerulea</emphasis>
Aubl.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hook." authorityName="Hook." box="[200,389,1986,2012]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Voyria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tenella">
<emphasis box="[200,312,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">V.tenella</emphasis>
Hook.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[404,569,1986,2012]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Gentianaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
